Multiple Regression

Today we are going to be looking at cases where the outcome can not be explained by one variable alone.

We are going to read in Life Expectancy data for countries over time.

The Global Health Observatory (GHO) data repository under World Health Organization (WHO) keeps track of the health status as well as many other related factors for all countries. The dataset related to life expectancy, health factors for 193 countries has been collected from the same WHO data repository website and its corresponding economic data was collected from United Nation website. Among all categories of health-related factors only those critical factors were chosen which are more representative.

le <- read_csv("Life Expectancy Data.csv") 
## 
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   Country = col_character(),
##   Status = col_character()
## )
## i Use `spec()` for the full column specifications.
#Need to clean up the variable names to make it easier to work with
names(le) <- str_replace_all(names(le), " ", "_")
names(le) <- str_replace_all(names(le), "-", "_")
names(le) <- str_replace_all(names(le), "/", "_")

#Let's take a quick look at our Outcome Variable, Life Expectancy
summary(le$Life_expectancy)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   36.30   63.10   72.10   69.22   75.70   89.00      10
#Since Life Expectancy is our outcome variable, we don't want any missing values in that column.
le <- le %>% drop_na(Life_expectancy)

Exploring the Dataset

Lets start by exploring the distribution of the Life_expectancy variable and possible other variables of interest.

le %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = Life_expectancy)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Average life expectancy appears to peak around the mid-70s, with some country-years having much lower values.

Lets now start to explore Life Expectancy vs.other possible important variables

# Another upward trend

So far it appears that as BMI, GDP, and Alcohol use increase, so does Life Expectancy. Obviously, there are probably a lot more variables at play here.

One variable that might have an impact could be the status of the country, whether it is considered Developing or Developed.

We now need to look at the Status variable, as we did the others.

le %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Status, y = Life_expectancy)) + geom_boxplot()

le %>% 
  group_by(Status) %>% 
  summarize(min = min(Life_expectancy),
            max = max(Life_expectancy),
            mean = mean(Life_expectancy)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Status, y = mean, color = Status)) + 
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = min, ymax = max), size = 1.5) + 
  geom_jitter(data = le, aes(x = Status, y = Life_expectancy), alpha = .5) +
  theme_classic()

Looking at the Development Status of the country, it appears this is something we need to take into account.

Lets add Status to the graphs to see what our data looks like

le %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = Life_expectancy, y = BMI, color = Status)) + geom_point(alpha = .3) + geom_smooth(method = "lm", lwd = 3)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 32 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 32 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# Interesting Difference in the effect of BMI on Developing vs. Developed Countries
 
le %>% ggplot(aes(x = Life_expectancy, y = log(GDP), color = Status)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", lwd = 3)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 443 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).

# Effect of GDP appears to be similar between Developing and Developed countries

Interactions

As we saw when looking at the previous graphs, sometimes a variable will a differential effect on another variable and sometimes it does not. This is when we need to investigate whether we want to use an interaction term so that different groups have different slopes.

# Let's start with a basic model looking at BMI and Life Expectancy
mod0 <- lm(Life_expectancy ~ BMI, data = le)

# This is a self-created function that will run through a bunch of the model checks that we normally run. We will do this a bunch of times today, so a function will allow us to save some time.

modCheck <- function(mod) {
 print(summary(mod))
 print(tidy(mod))
 print(glance(mod))
}
modCheck(mod0)

BMI is definitely a worthwhile variable to keep in mind, however when we looked at the graph earlier, BMI had a differential effect on the Development Status of the country.

mod6 <- lm(Life_expectancy ~ BMI * Status + log(GDP) + Total_expenditure + Income_composition_of_resources + Schooling + Polio + Alcohol, data = le)

We can look at the coefficients from this model in a plot if we like by using the dotwhisker package.

tidy(mod6) %>% 
  arrange(estimate) %>% 
  dwplot(dot_args = list(size = 2, color = "black"),
         whisker_args = list(color = "black"),
         vline = geom_vline(xintercept = 0, colour = "grey50", linetype = 2))

Stepwise Regression

Sometimes you go into an analysis with variables in mind that you want to explore. Youve done the research and you know the relationships that might be important. However, sometimes you have a dataset that is not easily understood. In this case, stepwise regression may be a good first step. Stepwise regression using a metric (AIC, RMSE, etc) to add or take away variables from a model to make the best model possible.

Use caution when using stepwise regression methods. Make sure to double check that the variables chosen make clinical/scientific/sociological sense. You also want to make sure you have properly cleaned your data and removed any variables from your data that you do not want to end up in the final model.

Stepwise regression should be used mostly as a starting place and not as a final model. Use it to test theories, not to finish your analysis.

The stepAIC function from the MASS package allows you to create models based off of the lowest possible AIC.

Lets first clean up our dataset a bit.

le_test <- le %>% drop_na() %>% dplyr::select(-Country)

Then create a full model containing all variables. Im dropping year because we will be looking

  full.model <- lm(Life_expectancy ~., data = dplyr::select(le_test, -Year))

We then use the stepAIC function on the full model. We can specify whether we want to start with an empty model and add variables one at a time (forward), we can specify whether we want to start with a full model and remove variables one at a time (backwards), or we can do a combination of both (both).

step.model <- stepAIC(full.model, direction = "both", 
                      trace = FALSE)

step.model$model

Logistic Regression

When we have an outcome that is binary, we want to move onto logistic regression. For this we are going to be using the following dataset:

From: Davide Chicco, Giuseppe Jurman: Machine learning can predict survival of patients with heart failure from serum creatinine and ejection fraction alone. BMC Medical Informatics and Decision Making 20, 16 (2020).

  • age: age of the patient (years)
  • anaemia: decrease of red blood cells or hemoglobin (boolean)
  • high blood pressure: if the patient has hypertension (boolean)
  • creatinine phosphokinase (CPK): level of the CPK enzyme in the blood (mcg/L)
  • diabetes: if the patient has diabetes (boolean)
  • ejection fraction: percentage of blood leaving the heart at each contraction (percentage)
  • platelets: platelets in the blood (kiloplatelets/mL)
  • sex: woman or man (binary)
  • serum creatinine: level of serum creatinine in the blood (mg/dL)
  • serum sodium: level of serum sodium in the blood (mEq/L)
  • smoking: if the patient smokes or not (boolean)
  • time: follow-up period (days)
  • [target] death event: if the patient deceased during the follow-up period (boolean)

Lets read in the data and take a look at our outcome variable DEATH_EVENT

hf <- read_csv("heart_failure_clinical_records_dataset.csv")
## 
## -- Column specification --------------------------------------------------------
## cols(

##   high_blood_pressure = col_double(),
##   platelets = col_double(),
##   serum_creatinine = col_double(),
##   serum_sodium = col_double(),
##   sex = col_double(),
##   smoking = col_double(),
##   time = col_double(),
##   DEATH_EVENT = col_double()
## )
hf %>% count(DEATH_EVENT)

## 1           0   203
## 2           1    96

About 32% of the patients in this dataset end up passing away.

Running Logistic Regressions

For this well use logistic regression to model the log odds of the binary response. That is, instead of modeling the outcome variable, \(Y\), directly against the inputs, well model the log odds of the outcome variable.

  • If \(p\) is the probability that a death occurs,

  • then \[\frac{p}{1-p}\] is the odds that a death occurs

  • and \[log(\frac{p}{1-p})\] is called the log odds

The log odds can be expressed as:

\[log(\frac{p}{1-p}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_1 + \cdots + \beta_k x_k\] Where \(\beta_0\) is the intercept, \(\beta_1\) is the increase in the log odds of the outcome for every unit increase in \(x_1\), and so on.

Modeling the log odds rather than the probability or the odds has the benefit of a linear model on the right-hand side and compared to probability that is constrained between 0 and 1, log odds have a wider range.

  • Probability ranges from 0 to 1
  • Odds range from 0 to Inf
  • Log odds range from -Inf to Inf

Logistic regression is a type of generalized linear model (GLM). We fit GLM models in R using the glm() function. It works like the lm() function except we specify which GLM to fit using the family argument. Logistic regression requires family=binomial.

The typical use looks like this:

mod <- glm(y ~ x, data=yourdata, family='binomial')
summary(mod)

In R, as in most statistical software, the outcome variable must be coded as 0/1 so that is why we did that earlier.

Just the intercept model

Looking at a model without any predictors will help us understand a bit more about the relationship between probability, odds, and log odds.

To fit a model without any predictors, we just model the outcome against 1 (the intercept).

glm_mod0 <- glm(DEATH_EVENT ~ 1, data=hf, family="binomial")
summary(glm_mod0)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = DEATH_EVENT ~ 1, family = "binomial", data = hf)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max  
## -0.880  -0.880  -0.880   1.507   1.507  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -0.7489     0.1239  -6.046 1.49e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 375.35  on 298  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 375.35  on 298  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 377.35
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

So -0.7489 is the log odds of dying for this population. What does this mean? Lets convert it to odds and to probability.

# extract just the log odds
summary(glm_mod0)$coefficients[1]
## [1] -0.7488578
# calculate the odds
exp(summary(glm_mod0)$coefficients[1])
## [1] 0.4729064

The odds are 0.472 to 1 that a random patient selected from this population will die.

What about the probability? Remember that odds = p / (1-p) so the probability of a death is odds / (1 + odds)

0.4729064/(1+0.4729064)
## [1] 0.3210702

32%, same as we calculated above.

hf %>%
  count(DEATH_EVENT) %>%
  mutate(prop = n / nrow(hf))
## # A tibble: 2 x 3
##   DEATH_EVENT     n  prop
##   <fct>       <int> <dbl>
## 1 0             203 0.679
## 2 1              96 0.321

Lets fit a logistic regression model assessing how the odds of death change with one categorical predictor we identified in EDA as important, anaemia.

Lets start by looking at the relationship between anaemia and a Death event occurring.

log_mod1 <- glm(DEATH_EVENT ~ anaemia, data = hf, family = "binomial")
summary(log_mod1)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = DEATH_EVENT ~ anaemia, family = "binomial", data = hf)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -0.9391  -0.9391  -0.8346   1.4361   1.5645  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -0.8755     0.1683  -5.201 1.98e-07 ***
## anaemia       0.2853     0.2492   1.145    0.252    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 375.35  on 298  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 374.04  on 297  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 378.04
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

The intercept corresponds to the log odds of death for someone without anaemia (-.8755).

The next coefficient is the log odds of death for someone with anaemia (.2853). Lets calculate the odds ratio for these.

exp(summary(log_mod1)$coefficients)
##              Estimate Std. Error     z value Pr(>|z|)
## (Intercept) 0.4166667   1.183321 0.005510708 1.000000
## anaemia     1.3301205   1.283050 3.141050074 1.287101

So 1.33:1 that someone with anaemia in this population will die compared to someone without. We can phrase it the other way as well: The odds are 0.42:1 that someone without anaemia will die, but it is much more conventional to interpret whichever odds is > 1.

Lets calculate 95% confidence intervals to get some estimate of the variability.

exp(cbind(OR = coef(log_mod1), confint(log_mod1)))
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                    OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.4166667 0.2971043 0.5756451
## anaemia     1.3301205 0.8154214 2.1697997

Note that the confidence interval crosses 1, which indicates a lack of significance.

What else can we learn from the output?

summary(log_mod1)
##

## glm(formula = DEATH_EVENT ~ anaemia, family = "binomial", data = hf)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  -0.8755     0.1683  -5.201 1.98e-07 ***
## anaemia       0.2853     0.2492   1.145    0.252    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 375.35  on 298  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 374.04  on 297  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 378.04
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Notice that for logistic regression, we no longer have R^2 as a metric of model fit. Instead we have deviance and the AIC, Aikaike Information Criterion. The AIC alone is not interpretable, but it is useful for comparing nested models. If you would like to use model selection in your research, please reach out to us for help with this if desired.

We can calculate a sort of pseudo-R^2 in the explained deviance, which is \[1 - \frac{Residual Deviance}{Null Deviance}\]

1-(log_mod1$deviance/log_mod1$null.deviance)
## [1] 0.003486293
devCheck <- function(mod) {
  print(tidy(mod))
  print(exp(cbind(OR = coef(mod), confint(mod))))
  print(paste("Model Fit:", round(1-(mod$deviance/mod$null.deviance), 5)))
}

devCheck(log_mod1)
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic     p.value

## 1 (Intercept)   -0.875     0.168     -5.20 0.000000198
## 2 anaemia        0.285     0.249      1.14 0.252
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                    OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.4166667 0.2971043 0.5756451
## anaemia     1.3301205 0.8154214 2.1697997
## [1] "Model Fit: 0.00349"

Now we are looking at the probability of the DEATH EVENT by age and ejection fraction

ggplot() + 
  geom_point(data = hf, aes(age, as.numeric(DEATH_EVENT) - 1), alpha = .1) +
  geom_point(data = newdata2, aes(age, pred, color = ejection_fraction))

Shows that as age and ejection fraction increase, the probability of a DEATH EVENT increases.
